         <abstract>
            <p>This paper describes some ways in which PC-based flight simulation can be
                            used to teach aircraft flight performance and flight testing to
                            aeronautical engineering students. Two PC-based flight simulation
                            programs are used here for this purpose: the Jeppesen FS200 PCATD and
                            Microsoft Flight Simulator 98. Examples of student flight test
                            assignments using these programs are given for cruise (straight and
                            level, unaccelerated) flight, climbs, descents (power off glide), and
                            for (level) maneuvering flight. Simulation flight test data from these
                            assignments are presented and compared to theory. It is concluded that
                            PC-based flight simulation can be a valuable tool for illustrating
                            flight performance and flight testing to aeronautical engineering
                            students and can be challenging, interesting and fun for students.</p>
         </abstract>
